{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30333546-0a07-451f-b2c4-082c3e679089","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app/).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If `dotnet tool` isn't available in your image, use the [global tool Docker image](https://mcr.microsoft.com/dotnet/sdk) or copy the tool in via `kubectl cp`.\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want a portable JSON file viewable in a browser.\n- For **off-CPU** analysis (thread waits, locks), add the `gc-collect` profile or use `dotnet-dump` instead.\n- To copy the trace out: `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace`","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3788e8a9-8062-4715-960f-db0c0eb9a426","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":330},"id":"7239cf1c-bb88-457e-a7e4-8761b55ad018","timestamp":"2026-04-03T00:53:06.293Z","parentId":"0d28c25a-df07-4cc9-b95e-f00004f421bf"}
